ing anyone reachable at the tap of a keyboard, enabling easy document shari=
ng, and automating workflows via integrations. It can be a company&#8217;s =
OS.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">To be the OS, it needs partners. Slack realizes that =
it can&#8217;t build the best of everything. It doesn&#8217;t even use its =
own video product internally; it uses Zoom. Instead, it wants customers to =
choose the software that works best for them for each thing that they do, a=
nd then make that software work better by integrating it into the company&#=
8217;s workflows and communications.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">As Butterfield puts =
it:&nbsp;</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1=
em 0;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>For whatever software our customers a=
lready use, or whichever software they use in the future, we&#8217;d like t=
o make their experience of those tools better because they use Slack&#8230;=
 Slack with Slack Branded Feature X is probably less valuable than Slack wi=
th Competitive Branded Feature X in the same slot, because now you&#8217;re=
 using Slack and you have an integration set up.</em></p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em =
